  "cultural_and_social_tips": [
    "Always greet with 'Salam' when entering a room — it's considered rude not to.",
    "Refusing tea (Atay) when offered is impolite — always accept at least one glass.",
    "Use your right hand when eating, handshaking, or handing things — the left is traditionally considered unclean.",
    "Dress modestly when visiting mosques or rural areas out of respect.",
    "Bargaining (negotiating price) in souks is expected and part of the culture.",
    "Friday is the holy day — many businesses close for midday prayers, and couscous is the traditional meal.",
    "Hospitality is sacred in Morocco — guests are treated like royalty.",
    "When eating from a communal Tagine, only eat from the section directly in front of you.",
    "Taking off your shoes when entering a Moroccan home with carpets is a common sign of respect.",
    "Bread (Khobz) is highly respected and should never be thrown in the garbage; it's usually given to animals if leftover.",
    "Kissing on the cheeks (usually 2 to 4 times) is a standard greeting between people of the same gender who know each other.",
    "Elders are highly respected; it's common to kiss the hand or head of grandparents or older relatives.",
    "During Ramadan, eating, drinking, or smoking in public during daylight hours is strictly forbidden."
  ]
